included.description: Dissertation focused on studying the functional relationship between neural activity and changes in cortical blood flow known as neurovascular coupling. A systems-level understanding of neurovascular coupling has critical consequences for functional neuroimaging techniques and the development of therapeutics for neurodegenerative disease. Managed all aspects of the research project from conceptualizing the research goals to designing experiments and developing tools to analyze high-dimensional imaging data. Co-authored 10 peer-reviewed journal articles and presented original research at 9 international conferences. Thrived in an environment of interdisciplinary teams of engineers, neuroscientists, physicists, and medical students.

included.name: Simultaneous multiplane in vivo nonlinear microscopy using spectral encoding
included.description: Conventional point-by-point imaging schemes for laser scanning microscopy limit acquisition speeds, particularly when imaging three-dimensional volumes. We report a novel approach that achieves parallelization of multiple fields of view through the use of spectral encoding. By focusing two or more beams of different wavelengths at different positions within a suitable tissue, fluorescence or second/third harmonic generation emissions from these regions can be uniquely separated. We demonstrate that this approach can allow simultaneous in vivo imaging of fluorescence in two planes within the living rodent cortex, and of second harmonic generation in fresh tissue.
